            <ArticleTitle>Immunotherapy in allergy and cellular tests: State of art.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>1595-1610</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText NlmCategory="UNLABELLED">The basophil activation test (BAT) is an in vitro assay where the activation of basophils upon exposure to various IgE-challenging molecules is measured by flow cytometry. It is a cellular test able to investigate basophil behavior during allergy and allergy immunotherapy. A panoply of critical issues and suggestive advances have rendered this assay a promising yet puzzling tool to endeavor a full comprehension of innate immunity of allergy desensitization and manage allergen or monoclonal anti-IgE therapy. In this review a brief state of art of BAT in immunotherapy is described focusing onto the analytical issue pertaining BAT performance in allergy specific therapy.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
